s sing play instruments and dance Marguerite meetings feature the membership seat chorus with leader the chantwl standing while Rose meetings include instruments like the tanbouwen tambourine baha wooden trumpet chakchak rattles guitar and gwaj scraper The celebrations both groups differ that Rose the English faction characterized noisiness movement participation rhythm and exuberance while Marguerite the French faction characterized melody discipline and restraint There vibrant tradition women singing factional songs related this rivalry Traditions common both factions include the Omans sort waltz Marches and the duple rhythm manpa maynan dance Kwadril and lakonmt are also performed Rose addition and other music performed for entertainment Saint Lucia also home styles used only for specific occasions These include work songs drinking songs funereal music and serenades and masquerades The latter two traditions are nearly extinct modern Saint Lucia The masquerade was celebration held near holidays like Easter and New Years Day which included orchestra consisting tanbou tenbal chakchak and bamboo flute This same ensemble also traditionally performs for cockfights merrygorounds and vocal serenades called swinal Lucian Creole The most widespread form Lucian work song the chant siay which accompanies the sawing wood The vocals are performed lead singer and two responding singers accompanied and tibwa duo Both instruments are played atypical manner The drum played the ground rather than upright and the tibwa percussion sticks are struck against bamboo wooden stick rather than the rim drum Lucian drinking songs are the chant abw which are rarely performed recent years Their traditional context however the wibt celebration held during Christmas time Chant abw are performed game which the singers seated long table take turns singing new song each time their turn comes Those who lasted the entire evening won prizes often bottle rum The tradition form Creole song and couple dance performed one couple with leader and chorus They are performed several contexts most notably funeral wakes include the anl matj anlawis and the The anlawis the only form which not responsorial Saint Lucia wakes are held the first and eighth night after person has died contrast other Caribbean islands which hold their wakes the first and ninth days Wakes often include music such the singing hymns and drumming Traditional music for wakes performed both inside and outside the deceaseds house The mourners inside the house sing from repertoire songs that are English and not French Creole because they are derived from the Englishusing songs Lucian churches The songs include both hymns and sankeys gospel songs and are generally responsorial led male singer with the slow unsyncopated responses the chorus unison The mourners outside the house traditionally perform drumming and kind responsorial song performed Creole and without accompaniment called kont These songs often related the death the deceased and may deal with the cause death the last words events surrounding the death Mourners also dance both the dbt and accompanied tibwa and The villages Grace Piaye and Laborie the southwest area Saint Lucia were known for unique songdance called the koutoumba The koutoumba was only performed for the death djin person descended from Africans who came the island the middle the 19th century The koutoumba unique among Lucian folk dance that performed sole dancer and using only two four lines text which evocative the songs atmosphere rather than narrative The last drummer who knew this tradition died 1986 AfroLucian religious tradition from the Djin people the Babonneau region Only one family from Resina modern Saint Lucia claims have the religious authority perform and pass the rituals based around three deities Eshu Shango and Ogun and similar the Nigerian Ogun festival Kls rituals involve contacting ones ancestors ask for protection especially good crops good health and good fortune has been underground for much its history and was only accepted the Lucian Roman Catholic Church the early 1960s rituals are accompanied the drumming the tanbou manman mother drum and the tanbou ich child drum which play four different rhythms specified moments these are the adan koudou and rhythms rituals also include singing and dance well feasting praying Ogun and the other gods the smashing the calabash appease Eshu the end the ceremony the display tools made iron and steel honor Ogun and smooth stones represent Shango who also receives ceremonially cleansed sacrificial ram Lucian popular music can traced back the 1940s when calypso became part the islands musical culture Calypso lyrical Trinidadian genre related several styles found through the Antillean music area Music scholar Jocelyne Guilbault has called calypso the primary way modern Lucians express social commentary Along with calypso Lucia has also imported the Trinidadian steelband and soca traditions Some Lucian calypsonians recorded the 1980s mostly 45RPM discs which remain largely unavailable today The Lucian music industry quite small scale due the islands small market its lack recording studios and record producers the widespread bootlegging cassettes and the general unavailability funding for musical ventures Saint Lucia home several radio stations including Radio Lucia and Radio Caribbean International which play variety popular music since 1989 Lucian radio stations have played increasing number programs about Lucian culture and the local Creole tongue Modern Saint Lucia has produced few popular musicians various styles but most closely associated with calypso music Popular Lucian musicians include Tru Tones Rameau Poleon Prolifik Disturbing Joan and Aimran Simmons Marie Selipha Sesenne Descartes known simply Sesenne was named Dame Commander the Order the British Empire for her work chantwelle and the promotion Saint Lucian traditional culture and music Saint Lucian folk dance and theater 